How does it work?
The RU-Fit™ model SR-3053 system
measures small changes in the fine motor
control performance as a function of time by
monitoring the strength, reaction times and
coordination of the thumb, index and small
fingers simultaneously. This patented and
FDA approved system is non-invasive, and
uses three independent load-cell force gauges
to collect the data used in the measurements.
These measurements allow you to monitor
and detect changes in the ability of your
client’s hands to accomplish asynchronous
tasks over time by using time-resolved force
evidence-based measurements.
The procedure consists of four one-minute
tests. During each one-minute test, data
points are collected every 1 millisecond,
providing 60,000 measurements each for the
thumb, index and small fingers for a total of
180,000 measurements for each one of the
four tests collected the during the procedure.
The system uses two tests on each hand.
The data are processed by our HIPAA
compliant remote servers within minutes and
all processed data are available for immediate
or delayed viewing from our secure website.
The practitioner may view, archive, print or
re-print these results at their convenience.
Therapy Documentation:
SR-3053 testing before chiropractic therapy
begins establishes a baseline which defines
the existing capabilities of the client, pre-
treatment. SR-3053 testing again after the
therapy allows for documentation of changes
in the client’s fine motor control due to the
applied therapy.
Long term treatments may be monitored to
show rate of improvements over time by
making daily, weekly or bi-weekly repeat
tests during the therapy. By repeating the
tests, re-injury may be detected if the cause of
the initial problem is due to something the
client does without awareness.
By monitoring coordination and reaction
times during therapy, the chiropractor can
document the effectiveness of the therapy
program and determine when modifications to
the program may be necessary. This system
will help to quantitatively determine when the
client has returned to his or her natural
capability level or when the improvement has
reached a plateau.
What Injuries or Issues Can Be
Detected and Monitored?
This system is designed to detect changes in
the fine motor control of the hands. Our
research has shown we have a 99% predictive
probability for detecting these changes. These
changes may be caused by many injuries or
diseases, such as (but not limited to):
• Sports injuries
• Car crash injuries
• Concussions
• Slips, trips or falls
• Carpal Tunnel Syndrome (CTS)
• Stroke
• Shoulder pain
• Lower back pain
Efficacy of Treatment:
By comparing tests completed prior to
treatment with tests completed after
treatment, improvements in the patient can be
documented and these results may be used to
modify treatment plans throughout the
treatment program. Multiple tests during
treatment will indicate the rate of
improvement and when the improvement has
reached a plateau, and no longer improves.

Insurance Reimbursement:
Reimbursements codes used include office

(97750), and collection and interpretation of

on the report level you need and use for your
practice.
